<TITLE> US stocks, dollar fall, bonds up </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW YORK, July 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - US stocks retreated on Tuesday after disappointing earnings reports raised concerns about the housing slump, while bonds rose on a flight to quality. The sell-off in US shares followed a retreat in European stocks. Chemical company DuPont Co. reported disappointing earnings and building materials company USG Corp. reported sharply lower earnings and said the housing downturn could continue for some time. Countrywide Financial Corp., the largest U.S. mortgage lender, reported a 33 percent decline in quarterly profit and slashed its full-year earnings outlook. At 10:30 a.m. (1430 GMT) the Dow Jones industrial average was down 80.15 points, or 0.57 percent, at 13,863.27. The Standard & Poor's 500 Index was down 10.94 points, or 0.71 percent, at 1,530.63 and the Nasdaq Composite Index was down 21.29 points, or 0.79 percent, at 2,669.29. The benchmark 10-year note was up 3/32 in price in early trading, pushing the yield down to 4.94 percent. The dollar hit a 15-year low against a basket of major currencies and a record low against the euro amid concerns problems in subprime lending will extend to other areas of the economy. The FTSEurofirst 300 index was down 1.4 percent on the day, with concerns about the export-damaging strength of the euro. Euro zone government bonds drew safe-haven support. Japan's Nikkei index rose 0.21 percent as bank shares rose. Oil prices fell for a third day on expectations of rising US fuel stockpiles and pledges from OPEC to pump more crude if needed. London Brent crude was down 1.4 percent at $75.78 a barrel after coming within $1 of life highs last we
